==English==

===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|kelh₁}}
* First attested in 1541.
* Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|acclāmātiō|acclāmātiō, acclāmātiōnis|calling, exclamation, shout of approval}}, from {{m|la|acclamo||shout approval or disapproval of, shout out at}}, from {{m|la|ad||toward}} + {{m|la|clamo||cry out}}
* Compare French {{m|fr|acclamation}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æk.lə.ˈmeɪ.ʃən/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪʃən|lang=en}}
* {{homophones|lang=en|acclimation}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# A [[shout]] of [[approbation]], favor, or assent; eager expression of [[approval]]; loud [[applause]].
#* '''1876''', {{w|Henry Martyn Robert}}, ''{{w|Robert’s Rules of Order}}'', Chicago: S.C. Griggs & Co., p. 100, Article IX, Section 46, note,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/9097/pg9097-images.html]</sup>
#*: Sometimes a member nominates a chairman and no vote is taken, the assembly signifying their approval by '''acclamation'''.
#* {{w|Robert Southey}}
#*: On such a day, a holiday having been voted by '''acclamation''', an ordinary walk would not satisfy the children.
# The process of electing a person to a post in the absence of other nominees.
#: ''With no one running against her, she won by '''acclamation'''''.
# {{lb|en|art}} A representation, in [[sculpture]] or on [[medals]], of people expressing joy.
#* {{w|James Elmes}}
#*: '''Acclamation''' medals are those on which laudatory '''acclamations''' are recorded.
# {{lb|en|political}} An [[oral]] [[vote]] taken without formal [[ballot]] and with much fanfare; typically an overwhelmingly affirmative vote.

